“I dare say you’re wondering why I don’t put my arm round your waist,” the Duchess said after a pause.
“Of course it is,” said the Duchess, who seemed ready to agree to everything that I said;
“I think I should understand that better,” Alice said very politely,
“A fine day, your Majesty!” the Duchess began in a low, weak voice.
“Let’s go on with the game,” the Queen said to Alice;
“Have you seen the Mock Turtle yet?”
They very soon came upon a Gryphon, lying fast asleep in the sun.

thing!” said the Queen, “and take this young lady to see the Mock Turtle, and to hear his history. I must go back and see after some executions I have ordered;” and she walked off, leaving Alice alone with the Gryphon.
The Gryphon sat up and rubbed its eyes: then it watched the Queen till she was out of sight: then it chuckled.

They had not gone far before they saw the Mock Turtle in the distance, sitting sad and lonely on a little ledge of rock, and, as they came nearer, Alice could hear him sighing as if his heart would break.
“This here young lady,” said the Gryphon, “she wants for to know your history, she do.”
“_I’ve_ been to a day-school, too,” said Alice;
“And how many hours a day did you do lessons?” said Alice, in a hurry to change the subject.
“That’s enough about lessons,” the Gryphon interrupted in a very decided tone: “tell her something about the games now.”
